112
00:07:25,029 --> 00:07:28,896
The second application example is
an electronic scale,

113
00:07:28,896 --> 00:07:32,529
a scale such as the ones
in trade,

114
00:07:32,529 --> 00:07:37,331
that allows to measure
a force, or a weight,

115
00:07:37,331 --> 00:07:42,973
by using strain gauges.

116
00:07:43,623 --> 00:07:46,772
This scale, here disassembled,

117
00:07:46,772 --> 00:07:51,826
is made of a deformable
mechanical structure

118
00:07:52,791 --> 00:07:58,021
where a part is linked to the
stationary part of the balance, the table,

119
00:07:58,021 --> 00:08:01,745
and another part that is
connected to the plate.

120
00:08:01,745 --> 00:08:08,063
Schematically, here, this element here,
is what we call a bearing neck,

121
00:08:08,063 --> 00:08:10,146
that is a deformable structure

122
00:08:10,146 --> 00:08:14,279
with the four necks
that are here very thin,

123
00:08:14,279 --> 00:08:19,453
and so we put a resistance here

124
00:08:19,453 --> 00:08:24,500
on the part that deforms itself,
and when we will push here on the plate

125
00:08:24,500 --> 00:08:29,067
all the structure will deform itself
and change the resistance.

126
00:08:29,067 --> 00:08:34,166
We can see here a picture a little bit more
detailed of such strain gauges.

127
00:08:35,751 --> 00:08:41,173
Here, schematically, to picture
the element in a better way,

128
00:08:41,173 --> 00:08:43,881
we see that it is a coil

129
00:08:44,816 --> 00:08:50,546
with L times the length of
a copper cable

130
00:08:50,989 --> 00:08:57,774
and if we pull on this gauge her,
each of these strands will lengthen

131
00:08:57,774 --> 00:09:01,653
and the section will decrease so the
volume remains the same

132
00:09:01,653 --> 00:09:05,023
So we have a resisitance
that will change.

133
00:09:05,023 --> 00:09:09,394
If we pull on the strain gauge,
the resistance will increase

134
00:09:09,394 --> 00:09:13,054
and if we compress
the strain gauge,

135
00:09:13,054 --> 00:09:14,780
the resistance will decrease.

136
00:09:14,784 --> 00:09:18,501
We see here on these two
sketches the bearing neck

137
00:09:18,501 --> 00:09:21,408
in its equilibrium position

138
00:09:22,218 --> 00:09:25,937
and when we apply a force
on the plate

139
00:09:25,937 --> 00:09:29,296
so we deform this extremity here
the other one remaining stationary

140
00:09:29,296 --> 00:09:31,438
and so the resistance,
or the strain gauge,

141
00:09:31,438 --> 00:09:32,966
that is positioned at this place

142
00:09:32,966 --> 00:09:36,824
will elongate, so we will increase
its resistance,

143
00:09:36,824 --> 00:09:39,669
while this one will
be compressed.

144
00:09:39,669 --> 00:09:41,423
We will decrease its resistance

145
00:09:41,423 --> 00:09:42,837
of a value ΔR.

146
00:09:42,837 --> 00:09:47,601
Here is the circuit used within
the electronic balance.

147
00:09:47,601 --> 00:09:50,757
We have four resistors

148
00:09:50,757 --> 00:09:53,795
where two of them are known and fixed.

149
00:09:54,493 --> 00:09:58,959
The two others are the strain gauge
resistors,

150
00:09:58,959 --> 00:10:01,039
and that are capable to fluctuate.

151
00:10:01,039 --> 00:10:03,762
At equilibrium, these resistors are equal

152
00:10:03,762 --> 00:10:08,675
and so the bridge is at equilibrium
the voltage Vab is equal to 0.

153
00:10:08,675 --> 00:10:13,967
Under stress, the bearing
neck will change.

154
00:10:13,967 --> 00:10:19,478
The resistor R3 will increase,
the resistor R4 decreases,

155
00:10:19,478 --> 00:10:24,710
and so at equilibrium Uab will be broken

156
00:10:24,710 --> 00:10:27,470
and a voltage between these
two points will appear.

157
00:10:27,470 --> 00:10:30,922
We find the equation that
we have expanded before,

158
00:10:30,922 --> 00:10:36,076
with the crossed products
that must be equal,

159
00:10:36,076 --> 00:10:40,513
the resistor R4 will be
changed of a value - ΔR,

160
00:10:40,513 --> 00:10:45,704
the resistor R3 will be modified
of a value + ΔR.

161
00:10:45,704 --> 00:10:51,927
We see in this equation that ΔR
can simply be changed here, compensate itself.

162
00:10:51,927 --> 00:10:55,494
And the voltage that
appears at the terminals,

163
00:10:55,494 --> 00:10:58,051
between the terminals A and B

164
00:10:58,051 --> 00:11:02,439
namely given bay this equation that
depends on the fluctuations of the resistor

165
00:11:02,439 --> 00:11:06,106
and therefore the deformation that
has been done on the scale.

166
00:11:06,106 --> 00:11:09,199
There will the be a voltage between
the points A and B that will appear,

167
00:11:09,199 --> 00:11:12,368
it is a little bit like the needle of the balance,
here that will

168
00:11:12,368 --> 00:11:18,889
deviate from the equilibrium position
if we continue our analogy.

169
00:11:18,889 --> 00:11:22,592
Note that we can arrange the
resistors in different ways

170
00:11:22,592 --> 00:11:25,803
to increase the sensibility of the circuit,

171
00:11:25,803 --> 00:11:29,647
eventually go from two gauges
to four gauges.

172
00:11:29,647 --> 00:11:33,378
But anyway, the big
advantage of this set up,

173
00:11:33,378 --> 00:11:35,884
is that it is indifferent to
external disturbances,

174
00:11:35,884 --> 00:11:37,980
for example the temperature.

175
00:11:37,980 --> 00:11:41,858
At equilibrium, if the circuit's
ambient temperature increases,

176
00:11:41,858 --> 00:11:44,150
then the bridge stays at equilibrium

177
00:11:44,150 --> 00:11:48,722
because all the resistors will
increase because of the temperature.

178
00:11:48,735 --> 00:11:50,514
And therefore, the equilibrium will be guaranteed.

179
00:11:50,514 --> 00:11:55,175
So we have seen a particular
circuit linked to metrology,

180
00:11:55,175 --> 00:11:57,766
it is the Wheatstone bridge.

181
00:11:57,766 --> 00:12:02,742
We have done the expansion of the
functioning in DC mode

182
00:12:02,742 --> 00:12:05,679
but it is also valid for
the alternative mode.

183
00:12:05,679 --> 00:12:07,918
We have seen that we could use this bridge
in two different ways

184
00:12:07,918 --> 00:12:09,757
either by searching for the equilibrium

185
00:12:09,757 --> 00:12:12,665
either by starting at equilibrium,
and moving away from this equilibrium

186
00:12:12,665 --> 00:12:16,890
and calculate the resistance fluctuations .

187
00:12:18,020 --> 00:12:21,059
This circuit has a lot of advantages,

188
00:12:21,059 --> 00:12:25,301
as being indifferent
to the temperature.

189
00:12:25,941 --> 00:12:29,349
It is clear now that, there are
many electronic devices

190
00:12:29,349 --> 00:12:31,602
that allow to
measure the resistances,

191
00:12:31,602 --> 00:12:34,295
and that make the circuit
a little bit obsolete, 

192
00:12:34,295 --> 00:12:37,990
but the structure of the bridge remains
used in many assemblies,

193
00:12:37,990 --> 00:12:40,546
even in embedded electronics,

194
00:12:40,546 --> 00:12:43,933
when it is not possible
